{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558856/1945080801/0441.xml":{"full_text":"Jfl 1 'X I ^W 1 VTTilrl associAted press\nuiiumumiui zwuiinuin ?yiur\n__. 4^r State and National Newt\nVoTt^-NQ- 2~31. WILMINGTON, N. C., WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 8, 1945 --ESTABLISHED 1861\nDirectors Of Atomic Bomb Project\nMaj Gen. Leslie R. Groves (seated), Army officer in charge\nthe government's atomic bomb project at Oak Ridge, Tenn., works\nin his office with his assistant, Brig. Gen. Thomas F. Farrell (right),\nseveral days before the first use of the bomb against Japan was\nannounced by President Truman Aug. 6. (AP Wirephoto).\nEm Barbers At Clinton\nKept Mum On New Bomb\nOAK RIDGE, Term., Aug. 7.\n(U.R) Tens of thousands of workers\nat the government\u2019s \u201cClinton En\ngineering Works\u201d and their fami\nlies struggled to act like normal\npersons today and it wasn\u2019t at all\neasy.\nFor months, some for years,\nthey had been living in an atmos\nphere of strain and secrecy. The\nknew they were working with com\nponent parts or the raw materials\nof a mighty war weapon. Very few\nof them had even an idea it was\nan atomic bomb but they knew\nwhatever it was, it was their coun\ntry\u2019s most valued secret.\nWorkers were asked not. to tell\ntheir wives. Wives were required\nnot to pass on any suspicions they\nmight have, particularly not to\ntheir children. No one was per\nmitted to own a camera. The gov\nernment was depending upon\neveryone\u2019s patriotism, but Army\nIntelligence of icers were every\nwhere to see that there was no in\ndiscretion. Even to leave this city\nof 75,000 persons which the govern\nment built in four years and owns,\nlock stock, and barrel, the resi\ndents needed a pass.\nToday they were excitedly dis\ncussing the honor which was theirs\n\u2014they were the pioneers who had\ncreated the means of controlling\natomic energy now focused in a\nweapon of incalcuable destructive\niorce but with awesome potentials\njf good. The residents gossiped on\nhe street corners about some\n(Continued on Page Two; Col 6)\n-V\nJOHNSON RITES SET\nFOR MONDAY NEXT AT\nSAN FRANCISCO, CALIF.\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 7.^ (U.R)\nfuneral Services for the late Sen.\nfiram W. Johnson, R., Calif., will\nje held in San Francisco next Mon.\nlay, it was announced today.\nThe body will leave here by\n;ra\u2019n Thursday night and is sched\njled to arrive in San Francisco\nVfonday morning. It wili be taken\nmmediately to the City Hall where\nt will lie in state. Burial will be\nn Cypress Lawn Cemetery in late\nifternoon.\nThe last rites are expected to be\nnibble, in accordance with John\nson\u2019s wishes.\nHis office revealed that Presi\nlent Truman, his former Senate\ncolleague, had sent a telegram of\ncondolence to the widow.\n\u201cMany years of association have\nendeared Hiram to all of us who\n[Continued on Page Two; Col 4)\nNINETEEN KILLED\nIN HOIST BLAST\nPORT ARTHUR, Ont., Aug. 7.\n\u2014(jp)\u2014At least 19 persons were\nkilled today in an explosion which\nwrecked storage elevator No. 5 of\nthe Saskatchewan Wheat Pool Ltd.,\nand officials of the concern said\nthe toll might reach 20 to 35 men.\nA score of seriously injured work\ners were taken to the hospital.\nHours after the blast many per\nsons still were missing, including\na number of soldiers on leave to\nwork in lakehead elevators.\nCause of the blast, which rock\ned the twin cities of Port Arthur\nand Fort William shortly after\n10 a. m. (Eastern War Time) was\nnot immediately determined, but\nit may have resulted from an ac\ncumulation of grain dust. The ele\nvator was located about three miles\nfrom the center of Port Arthur.\nThe grain vessel Sonora was\nloading at the Saskatchewan Pool\nelevator docks, but it was not\nknown immediately whether it had\nsustained any damage.\nMost of the men killed and in\njured were employed in the Ele\nvator workhouse where the grain\nis unloaded and cleaned before\nbeing placed in the storage annex\nfrom where it is loaded into ships.\nThe storage elevator was one of the\nlargest at the head of the Great\nLakes.\ni The blast blew out all four walls\nj me elevator. Four of the bodies\ni vere found 200 feet from the build\nmg,\nfiremen from Port Arthur and\nort William fought the flames\nar4 headed rescue squads seeking\nbead and injured.\nk is the worst explosion we\ne,'er \u201cJ(L said John Burton of\nme Eastern Terminal Elevator i\ncompany. whose office is about 400\neeJ from the Saskatchewan Pool\nbuilding, ft.\nA sheet of flame 200 to SOfl feet\nrg swept from the workhouse at\nbe instant 0f the explosion and\n,v'\u00aes collapsed. Only the con\ne\u2018e beams are standing.\u2019\u2019\n\nWEATHER\nbu^HiNGT0*' Alie. 7.\u2014(ip)\u2014Weather\nfail for r,hDorI, \u00b07 temperature and rain\nthe rrm!?e ,24 h\u00b0urs ending 8 p. m. in\ncishere Pa cot,on Snowing areas and\n^ation\nAlpena Hlgh Low Prcc*\nAsheville 73 ^7 *34\nAtlanta 78 68 *53\nAtlantic City'\u201d 73\n^rrri.nsham 1 87\nEoston S\u2019am 83 71 .94\nEuitalo 64 57 -47\nBurlinetnn 75 69\nChicago 95 58 -39\nCincinnati IS SS -39\nCleveland ?S I?\nDciits 73 61 -35\nDenver\nDetroit 78 59 .01\nBuluth H 64\nll paso 72 54 .03\nforth Worth 97 79\nChlvest\u2122 89 77\n\u2018tchsonvme 99 78\nSn,3\u00bb U\nfsr\u00a3,=r 8 g 5\nh Angeles 8? 74 -91\nJtouisvilie 87 67\nJ'mphis 8S I7\n|tian S it 97\nliobjiISt' Psul 76 58 .02\nvtw Orleans\" SI 74\n\u2022\u20196\\v York- 9o 77\nNorfolk 79 63\n&\u00b0enix 37 73\n^ttsburgh\ncrthd Me- 8\u00b0 64 .40\n\"H 8 g f,\ni s g\n5av-n.hnnsco 61 54\nSc:'\u201eUh 98 74\nta-r-n 75 60\niHsburg 93 78\nsas^ s s\n\"g,on 91 79 1.03\nAtomic Bomb\nHits Center\nOf Jap City\nCONCUSSION ALARMING\nCrew Of Fort Feels Effecl\nOfDetonationlO\nMiles Away\nGUAM, Aug. 7.\u2014(JP)\u2014America\u2019s\nnew weapon, the atomic bomb,\nstruck squarely in the center of the\nindustrial city of Hiroshima Aug\n6 (Pacific time) with a flash and\nconcussion that brought an excla\nmation of \u201cMy God\u201d from a bat\ntie-hardened Superfortress crew II\nmiles away.\nCrewmen who carried the awful\nnew bomb which is declared to\nhave an explosive power the equi\nvalent of bombs that 2,000 Super\nfortresses would have had to carry\npreviously although they were far\naway, felt the concussion like a\nclose explosion of anti-aircraft fire.\nCol. Paul W. Tibbets, Jr., oi\n1629 S. W. Sixth St., Miami, Fla.,\nwho piloted the Superfortress and\nNavy Capt. William S. Parsons, oi\nSanta Fe, N. Mex., Navy ordnance\nexpert, described the explosions as\n\u201ctremendous and awe-inspiring.\u201d\nNeither man could give an es\ntimate of what damage the bomb\nhad wrought but they declared it\n\u201cmust have been extensive.\u201d\nThere is reason to believe, how\never, that this Southern Honshu\ncity of 343,000 no longer continues\nto exist.\n\u201cIt was 0915 (9:15 a.m.) when\nwe dropped our bomb and we turn\ned the plane broadside to get the\nbest view,\u201d said Capt. Parson.\n\u201cThen we made as much distance\nfrom the ball of fire as we could.\n\u2018We were at least ten miles away\nand there was a visual impact\neven though every man wore col\nored glasses for protection. We had\nbraced ourselves when the bomb\nwas gone for the shock and Tib\nbets said \u2018close flak\u2019 and it was\njust like that\u2014a close burst of\nanti-aircraft fire.\n\u201cThe crew said \u2018My God\u2019 and\ncouldn\u2019t believe what had happen\ned.\n\u201cA mountain of smoke was go\n(Continued on Page Two; Col 1)\nCROSLEY RADIO\nEMPIRE CHANGES\n\nCINCINNATI, Aug. 7.\u2014<\u00a3>>\u2014 The\nradio and household appliance em\npire assembled through 25 years\nby Powell Crowley, Jr., passed into\nthe hands of the Aviation Corpora\ntion of New York today, with the\ntransfer to Crosley of checks to\ntaling $12,000,000.\nThe amount represented only\nCrosley\u2019s personal share and shares\nheld by his family and in trust,\nin a $21,000,000 deal announced\nJune 19.\nIn handing the checks to Crosley\n\u2014who smiled broadly before a bat\ntery of news cameramen\u2014Irving\nB. Babcock, AVCO president, of\nNew York, remarked that of 545.\n000 shares involved, more than\n400,000 have been submitted for\nsale at an agreed $39 per share.\nBabcock succeeds Crosley as\npresident of the Crosley Corpora\ntion which will retain its >rporate\nidentity as an AVCO subsidiary.\n(Continued on Page Two; Col 3)\nCARRIER PLANES\nHIT CHINA COAST\nThree-Day Attack Report\nr ed By Nimitz; Results\nSatisfactory\nGUAM, Wednesday, Aug. 8.\u2014(U.R\n\u2014Swarms of carrier planes on\nthe U. S. Pacific Fleet swept the\nChina coast for three days ending\nMonday in the first major naval\naction against the enemy in a week,\nAdm. Chester W. Nimitz announced\ntoday.\nStriking the China coast for the\nfirst time since the sweeps which\npreceded the invasion of Luzon in\nJanuary, the carrier planes blasted\nmilitary installations, shot down\nfour Japanese planes, destroyed\na large barge and damaged a small\ncoastal cargo vessel.\nliie sweeps were made South of\nShanghai, and among military in\nstallations damaged were build\nings and a seaplane base on Ting\nhai Island Southeast of Shanghai.\nThe assault was made by carriers\nof Vice Adm. Jesse B. Oldendorf\u2019s\nnaval force operating in the vicin\nity of the Ryukyus Islands and the\nEast China Sea. That force is not\npart of Adm. William F. Halsey\u2019s\nThird Fleet which has been under\na blackout since July 30 after a\nthree week air-sea bombardment\nof the Japanese mainland.\nOther carrier planes, striking\nfar to the East, were disclosed to\nhave battered the by-passed Jap\nanese garrison on Wake on August\n6, destroying or damaging small\ncraft, buildings and other installa\ntions. Carrier planes and a battle\nship had attacked Wake August 1.\nNimitz said the China sweeps\nwere made on Saturday, Sunday\nand. Monday.\nThe attack on Wake was another\nharassing assault against the iso\nlated enemy garrison, estimated to\nnumber no more than 2,000 starv\ning men, cut off from homeland\nsupply lines.\nNimitz also disclosed that other\nplanes sank or damaged 10 Japa\nnese ships in sweeps from Korea\nto the Kuriles.\nSearch privateers of Fleet Air\nWing One Monday sank four small\ncargo vessels in the Tsushima\nStrait between Korea and Japan,\ndamaged a fourmasted schooner\non the Korean coast and strafed a\nradar station in the Danjo Islands\nWest of Kyushu.\nOn the same day search Marin\ners of this wing sank a motor\nlaunch and damaged two light\nhouses on the China coast.\nEarly Tuesday morning, a night\nflying Mitchell medium bomber of\nthe same wing rocketed an enemy\nvessel of unidentified type in the\nTsushima straits.\nPrivateers of Fleet Air Wing 18\nsank a 300-foot cargo ship off the\nSouthern coast of Honshu on Tues\nday.\nPrivateers of Fleet Air Wing\n(Continued on Page Two; Col 4)\n-\u2014-v\nMORE INEXPENSIVE\nSHOES TO BE MADE\nAVAILABLE SHORTLY\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 7.\u2014(\u00a3>)\u2014A\nlarger supply of inexpensive shoes\nwas forecast today as the War Pro\nduction Board lifted controls on the\nnumber of pairs that may be pro\nduced.\nThe revocation covers rationed\nand non-rationed lines of adults\u2019,\nchildren\u2019s and infants\u2019 shoes which\nsell at retail at an estimated range\nof $1.25 to $6.25.\nWPB predicted improved supply\nin about 60 days, but said total\nproduction still would be below\nprewar volume. Both leather and\nnon-leather, work and dress types\nare covered by the order.\nPreviously all shoe production\nhad been restricted to specified\npercentages of base period output.\nControls are being lifted for in\nexpensive types to encourage\nmanufacture of these types, WPB\nsaid. The OPA announced Satur\nday that a wide variety of shoes\nretailing for $3.50 a pair or less\nwill be released from rationing,\neffective August 27 through Octo\nber 13.\n-V\nNavy Approves $800,500\nBuilding For Lejeune\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 7.\u2014 (JP)\nHie Navy today approved two\nprojects for North Carolina calling\nfor an expenditure of $830,500. They\nare:\nConstruction of quarters for mar\nried Marine officers at Camp Le\njeune, $800,500; and four addition\nal wells at Edenton, $30,000.\nSenator Hoey (D.-N.C.) said he\nhad been informed the projects\nwill be built subject to war con-\niitions.\nCapture Of Secret Note\nFixed Dunkerque Escape\nFRANKFURT, Germany, Aug. 7.\n\u2014(#)\u2014The accidental discovery of\na secret German document enabled\nBritish to evacuate 330,000 men\nfrom the trapped beaches of Dun\nkerque, the U. S. Army disclosed\ntoday.\n\u201cThis was the paper that lost\nthe war for Germany because it\nopened an escape hatch through\nwhich the core of the British re\ngular army slipped through and\ngave Britain at least the sem\nblance of enough strength to hold\non until* Russia and the United\nStates were drawn to her aid,\u201d\nan intelligence officer of G-2 said.\nAt an hour when the French were\nbeing slaughtered and the British\nwere making a desperate effort to\nevacuate their helpless divisions, a\nmember of the German general\nstaff on a reconnaissance mission\npushed too far ahead of his own\nlines and was fired upon by a\nBritish patrol.\nThe Nazi officer and his men\ntook off across the fields but their\nvehicle was set afire and was\ncaptured by the patrol. In it was\na copy of a surprise attack in the\nCalais region aimed at cutting off\nthe British escape.\nThe document fell into the hands\nof the commander of a small Bri\ntish force screening the Dunkerque\nbeaches only a few hours before\nthe attack was scheduled to be\ngin.\nIt foretold a hook movement by\na German force moving up from\n(Continued on Page Two; Col 2)\nAtonalBomb Blast Wipes Out Over Four\nSqr^e Miles Of Hiroshima, Completely\nDestroying Five Major Industry Plants\n60 Per Cent\nOf City Now\nDemolished\nPHOTOS SHOW RUINS\nGen. Spaatz Releases News\nEagerly Awaited By\nAllied Nations\nBy WILLIAM F. TYREE\nUnited Press War Correspondent\nGUAM, Wednesday, Aug. 8\u2014(UR)\u2014\nThe first atomic bomb dropped on\nHiroshima completely destroyed an\narea of four and one-tenth square\nmiles\u201460 per cent of the city\u2019s\nbuilt-up area\u2014and wiped out five\nmajor industrial targets with a tre\nmendous blast which obliterated\nthe city in a cloud of boiling smoke\nand flame, it was disclosed today.\nAn announcement by Gen. Carl\nA. Spaatz, commander of the Stra\ntegic Air Forces, gave the news\nthat had been anxiously awaited for\nmore than 24 hours.\nThe single atomic bomb had\nwiped out more than half of the\ncity of 343,000 in a terrifying ex\nplosion which bpaatz said equalled\na raid by 2,000 B-29s.\nMen of the Superfortress crew\nwho unleashed nature\u2019s harnessed\nfury on the helpless Japanese em\npire had described the fearful ef\nfects of that one bomb. Then,\nwhen the smoke that hung like a\ndeath pall over the stricken city\nhad cleafed, reconnaissance photo\ngraphs revealed the terrible ex\ntent of the destruction.\nSpaatz announced that the five\nmajor industrial plants within the\nfour and one-tenth square mile area\nhad been destroyed.\nThe force of the great explosion\nwreaked additional damage outside\nthe \u201ccompletely destroyed area\u201d,\nhe said.\nIt was obvious that crippling\nblow had been dealt to Hiroshima,\nlocated on the Southern section of\nthe main island of Honshu about\n400 miles Southwest of Tokyo.\nMilitary supply depots and factor\nies producing large guns, tanks,\nmachine tools and aircraft parts\nare in the congested city.\nThe Japanese already had ad\nmitted that destruction within\nHiroshima was so great that they\nthemselves had been unable to as\ncertain immediately the full extent\nof damage.\nLIBERATORS BLAST\nTWO KYUSHU CITIES\nMANLIA, Wednesday, Aug. 8.\u2014\nOf)\u2014More than 300 Liberators,\nMitchells and Invaders of the Far\nEast Air Forces struck heavily at\ntwo Southern Kyushu cities Mon\nday with fire bombs and jellied\ngasoline, producing great fires and\nexplosions throughout the target\narea.\nThe manufacturing city of Kago\nshima took the hardest impact as\nmore than 200 Liberators of the\nFifth and Seventh AAF\u2019s, escort\n(Continued on Page Three; Col 5)\n_v\nTRUMAN MAY GET\nOPA-WPB WRANGLE\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 7\u2014 (JP)\u2014An\nOPA-WPB wrangle involving basic\nreconversion policies was reported\ntoday to be tagged for arbitration\nby President Truman.\nThe dispute between the Office\nof Price Administration and the\nWar Production Board is pitched\non differences concerning the gov\nernment\u2019s inexpensive clothing pro\ngram.\nBut the issue is said to have\ngrown so that it now embraces\nfundamental price stabilization, as\nwell as WPB\u2019s place in the re\nconversion picture.\nThe quarrel developed when\nWPB began to consider abolishing\nits far-reaching order earmarking\nabout 75 per cent of all civilian fab.\nrics for low and moderately priced\ngarments. WPB is said to feel the\norder is too broad in view of cuts\nin military requirements for cloth\ning, and that it can be replaced\nby a regulation of lesser scope.\nThe current WPB order, known\nas M-388, was put into effect sev\neral weeks ago, along with a com\npanion OPA measure designed to\nroil back overall clothing costs 6 to\n7 per cent.\nOPA officials, when they learned\nWPB might abandon M-388, protest\ned that the price regulation would\nje unworkable without adequate\n'abric controls.\n(Continued on Page Two; Col 4)\n[_ Where Atomic Bomb Was Made At Oak Ridge, Tenn.\nThis is an aerial view of one of the big factories at Oak Ridge, Tenn., near Knoxville, where the\nnew atomic bomb was developed. President Truman personally issued a statement through the White\nHouse Aug. 6, disclosing existence of the bomb, des cribed as the most terribly destructive force ever\nharnessed by man. The disclosure was made just after the first atomic bomb was dropped on the city\nof Hiroshima, Jap sea port and army base. Note that the factory buildings have few windows except on\nthe top story. (AP Wirephoto).\nI\nPRESIDENT FACES\nCONTROVERSIES\nChief Executive Arrive:\nHome From Potsdam In\nGood Spirits\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 7\u2014 <U.R>\nPresident Truman, back in th\nUnited States after a one montl\nabsence overseas, was en route t\nWashington tonight to report ti\nthe nation by radio within the nex\nfew days on the results of the Bij\nThree conference at Potsdam.\nThere also was speculation tha\nhe soon may issupe a new surren\nder ultimatum to Japan, warn\ning the enemy to quit or be de\nbastated by the fury of the atomii\nbomb.\nThe presidential cruiser Augusta\ncarrying Mr. Truman a*id hi:\nparty home from Europe, dockec\nat Newport News at 4:45 p. m\n(EWT). A half hour later, the\npresidential party entrained foi\nWashington.\nAwaiting Mr. Truman\u2019s returr\nto the White House were a num\nber of pressing domestic and in\nternational problems.\nToping the domestic list are\nmatters dealing with reconversion.\nMembers of the Senate War In\nvestigating committee, which he\nformerly headed, plan to see Mr.\nTruman this week if possible tc\nadvocate a one-man rule of wai\nmobilization and reconversion.\nThey plan to tell him that efforts\nto achieve orderly reconversion\nwithout hampering production for\n4.U _ n -r: --u ^v.\ncreasingly difficult because of nc\ncentralized control. They seek tc\nvest in one authority to compel the\nArmy, Navy, WPB, WLB and OPA\nto pull together whenever they\nencounter differences.\nMr. Truman also will be asked\nto put his support behind com\nmittee demands that the Army\ndischarge experienced coal miners\nand railroad workers to help the\ndomestic economy workers.\nAnother problem concerns Con\ngressional demands that the size\nof the Army be reduced from 7,\n000,000 to 3,500,000.\nSenate members also look to Mr.\nTruman to take the lead in pro\nmoting a definite full employment\nprogram for the postwar era.\nThe President will be confronted\nwith severe criticism of the Big\nThree agreement by Sen Arthur H.\nVandenberg, R.K Mich., No. 1 Re\npublican on the Senate Foreign Re\nlations committee. Vandenberg has\nassailed the \u201cindefinite reference\u201d\n;o free elections in Poland and free\npress in European areas under\nRussian influence. He demands\nverification.\nThat question may be dealt with\nay Mr. Truman in his radio re\n(Continued on Page Two; Col 2)\n-V\nFIRST TRAIN ARRIVES\nBERLIN, Aug. 7.\u2014(fP)\u2014The first\nJnited States Army passenger train\narrived in Berlin today carying 741\nroops of the 82nd Airborne Di\nvision. Eleven other trains will\n\u2019ring in the rest of the division\n:rom Epinal, France, to relieve\nhe Second Armored Division as\nhe permanent U. S. Occupation\nrorce in the German capital.\nThieves Knot Pants\nOf Poolroom Victims\nI _ _\nCHELSEA, Mass., Aug. 7.\u2014\n(U.R)\u2014Two holdup men entered\nHenry Gordon\u2019s Pool room to\nday, took $80 from the proprie\ntor and three customers, the\nforced all four at gunpoint to\ntake off their trousers.\nAfter knotting the legs of the\ndiscarded trousers, the thieves\nfled.\nCLEARINGHOUSE\nRECEIPTS SLUMP\nAccording to a report yesterday\nissued by David M. Darden, sec\nretary of the Wilmington Clearing\nHouse Association, it was indicat\ned that the City\u2019s bank deposits foi\nJuly had slumped more than 1C\nmillion dollars to a reported fig\nure of $27,732,635.70.\nAccording to a statement issued\nby Mr. Darden today, these fig\nures were Clearing House receipts\nand not bank deposits. The Morn\ning Star is glad to make this cor\nrection.\nThe report from Mr. Darden dis\nclosed that Clearing House receipts\nfor June were $37,847,364.08. Re\nceipts for these two months also\nshowed a decrease when compar\ned to $39,461,914.65 and $34,475,496.\n15 for June and July of last year,\nrespectively.\nReason for the decrease in acti\nvities such as these were attribut\ned to the closing of camp Davis\nand the cessation of other activi\nties in this area, Mr. Darden said.\nTotal Clearing House receipts for\nthe first seven months of this year\nwere reported at $250,833,444.41,\ncompared to $273,522,536.95 for the\nfirst seven months of 1944.\nJAP CABINET CALLED\nNEW YORK, Aug. 7.\u2014(/P)\u2014The\nJapanese cabinet has been called\ninto special session to discuss \u201cin\nternal and foreign matters,\u201d a\nBBC broadcast quoting Toko Radio\nand heard by NBC said today. BBC\nsaid the Japanese wording was in\nterpreted to mean a discussion of\nthe Hiroshima atomic bomb raid.\nCHINESE TROOPS\nCAPTURE TANCHUK\nCity Taken During Ad\nvance On South China\nPort Of Canton\nCHUNGKING, Aug. 7. \u2014(U.R)\u2014\nChinese troops driving from two\ndirections on the great South China\nport of Canton have captured Tan\nchuk and Yeungkong, a communi\nque announced today amid authori\ntative reports that the Japanese\nare further consolidating their for\nces by evacuating Luichow penin\nsula and the Amoy area.\nTanchuk, former U. S. 14th Air\nForce base on the south bank of\nthe West (Si) river leading to Can\nton, was completely occupied Aug.\n4. The victorious Chinese are push\ning on down the river toward their\nnext objective of Tengyun, 26 air\nline miles to the east and within\n(Continued on Page Two; Col 5)\nTOP RANKING NAZIS\nTO BE TRANSPORTED\nTO NUERNBERG SOON\nLONDON Aug. 7.\u2014 (H) \u2014Top\nranking Nazis held as prisoners of\nwar will be moved shortly from\nMondorf, Luxembourg, to the\nNuernberg jail, where they will be\nheld for the approaching major\nwar crimes trial, it was disclosed\ntoday.\nThey will lose their status as wa\nprisoners and be held without bail\nas civil criminals.\nSupreme Court Justice Robert\nH. Jackson, Chief United States\nWar Crimes prosecutor, declined\nto divulge the identity of the group\nto be removed, pending their ar\nrival in Nuernberg.\nHe would not say whether they\nwere being transferred as a\nsecurity precaution against any\ndesperate attempt by fanatical\nNazis to deliver their erstwhile\nleaders. They will be moved in\nsmall groups under guard.\nWitnesses Insist France\nHad Pact With Britain\nPARIS, Aug. T\u2014(fP)\u2014Two witness\nes, testifying in defense of. Marshal\nHenri Philippe Petain, insisted to\nday that Britain concluded a se\ncret agreement with the Vichy,\ngovernment after the fall of\nFrance. One named Lord Halifax,\npresent British Ambassador t o\nWashington, as a principal inter\nmediary.\nThe allegations were made in\nthe face of official British denials\nof such a secret negotiation.\nThe agreement, the witnesses as\nserted, related mainly to obtaining\nFrench assurances that the French\nFleet would not be used against\nthe British, that colonial bases and\nareas would be denied the Ger\nmans and that Vichy would refrain\nfrom attempting to regain over\nseas areas then under control of\nGen. De Gaulle\u2019s Free French\nforces.\nIn return, both witnesses testi\nfied, Britain consented to relax her\nblockade and permit French ship\nping to pass through the Straits of\nGibraltar and bound herself to\nfurnish certain needed foodstuffs to\nFrance.\nThe witnesses were Jacques\nChevallier, former Vichy Secre\ntary-General of Education, and\nAdmiral Jean Fernet, former Sec\nretary General of the Presidency\nCouncil.\nThe defense was counting heavi\nly on. their testimony to support\nthe contention that Petain, far\nfrom collaborating with the Ger\nmans and plotting against the\n(Continued on Page Tr%; Col 3)","height":"27396","width":"20752"}}
